segments.text: All right.
Let's start with your background.
Could you summarize your early background?
Summarize my early background?
And how it prepared you for being a test pilot and an astronaut.
A lot of luck was involved because my early background consisted of doing just what I wanted to do, which would be an airplane pilot.
So when I went to the University of Texas I took aeronautical engineering because I thought it would make me a better airplane pilot.
So I was an aeronautical engineer and then I went to Navy flight training and then became a test pilot and then ended up being an astronaut.
So each step built on the previous step, although a lot of it was luck.
Particularly the transition from test pilot to astronaut because when I
Began all this, I never even thought about astronauts or space flight or anything like that.
Okay, you said you went into NASA as a naval aviator.
How important do you feel that that was in your selection and also your career?
Would it have been different had you gone in as a civilian?
As a civilian or you mean an Air Force or something like that?
Well, no, just basically as a civilian without the military, the active military that you went in on.
Well, now, to be an astronaut, you've got to have, at that period, you had to have lots of high-performance aircraft flying equipment.
You can only get that in the military.
So everybody that came in, came in as someone that had been in the military to amass the flight experience.
Once you were in, I don't think it really made a lot of difference.
as long as you were perceived as a pilot kind of person.
Because, for example, Neil Armstrong came in as a civilian, even though he had formerly been, I guess, in the Navy.
So I think as long as you were perceived as a pilot kind of person, that it didn't make any difference whether you were Air Force, Navy, Marines, or civilian.
All right.
You spent 18 years at NASA, 1963 to 1981.
How did your participation or the role you played change over those years?
Well, when you first get to NASA, you're in a very much of a training situation where
you're trying to mostly understand what the job is you've been hired to do.
I mean, you want to go fly in space, but you really don't have the opportunity and they have you doing a lot of other support sorts of things and training things.
And so you're, at least I was a little bit lost trying to understand what my function was other than just, I kept wanting somebody to tell me what to do, which they never did.
After you've been there a number, for a while, then you're assigned to a flight crew

Then you begin training for a mission and that's, it's harder work but it's simpler because you have a certain thing to do in a certain length of time and so you can sit down and determine how to do it.
Now in my case it was very fortunate because

I work with Pete Conrad, and he knew very much how to train for missions and what to do on space missions, so he taught me quite a lot, much more than maybe most of the other people, just because he knows a lot.
So in that phase of your time there, as long as you're on a flight crew, on a backup flight crew, you're training for a mission or flying it or then getting ready to train for the next one and
So you're doing that function which is the most interesting function there and of course the function that you always want to be in.
Then after the Russian mission, I was the backup commander of that mission,
then there was quite a way before anybody flew in space shuttle.
And so all of us were in a mode where we worked on the space shuttle in an engineering sense, engineering supports it.
A little bit like when I first came there, except this time some of the new ones worked for me doing the same thing.
As time passed, they selected people to fly the early shuttles, and I wasn't selected to do that.
I was selected to work with the new astronaut candidates and serve sort of as an administrative officer for all the astronauts.
So I did that for the last two years that I was at NASA, and I enjoyed it very much.
It would have been very frustrating to me if I hadn't flown to be in that role, but having flown to be in that role was...

nice, I enjoyed working with the people, and it was sort of like paying a little of the debt I had for having had some nice experiences, so all in all, I felt my career at NASA was, although I would never have done it exactly that way at the time, looking back on it, it turned out really nice, so I've been very happy about the 18 years, and felt that
Felt that I stayed long enough so that I was ready to go.
One of the things, I liked it being at NASA and I wanted to make sure that I didn't leave too early and then look back on it and wish that I were still there.
And that wasn't the case.
I felt like I was there until I finally said, you know, it's time for me to go.
So that felt good also.
And that's the way I feel now.
Okay.
What impact did your career have on your family?
Well, it had a big impact on my family, although I'm not sure exactly how it had the impact.
If I just looked at the results of my family, then I would say that it had a big impact.
First of all, I guess was my son, who was, when I went to the moon, he was about, let's see, I was 69.
And, uh, he was born in 55, so that would make him 14 years old.
Um, seemed to have a big effect on him.
The fact that I was gone a lot, uh, seemed to, um, seemed to make, seemed to make him, uh, I don't know what aspect of it, but he grew up to be a fairly rebellious, uh, son.
And he, uh,
He never wanted, and still doesn't, tends to not want to do things in the way he thinks that I might do them.
So he, somehow over this period, he got the feeling that he wanted to live his life differently than I did.
Whether that would have happened if I hadn't been in the space program or not, I don't know.
But that is an effect that occurred.
My daughter, who was seven years old when I went to the moon, she didn't seem to bother her so much.
And so I see her as growing up in rather a normal fashion and seems to behave...
with good and bad features of, uh, that, uh, of, uh, she's a freshman at the university of Texas.
So, and she's probably going to do real well there.
Uh, my marriage, I was divorced about five years ago.
And I think probably the space program had a lot to do with that in that, uh, when you're gone a lot and, uh, the running of the family and the decisions moves over to the woman,

Then when you come back, as I did five years or so after I got back, then the man then wants to take over the decisions, and that gets difficult because it's a lot more fun in a family to make decisions than follow them.
So I think that the space program had a big effect on my family, and whether or not it would have had it if I had stayed in the Navy, I don't really know.
But it did, in fact, have a big effect.
When you were growing up, your generation was just ahead of the youth movement and Vietnam War demonstrations.
Some of the newer astronauts today are from that generation.
Do you see any indication of the youth trend in the 60s?
Do you see any effects from that in some of the newly chosen astronauts?
No, but it may be because I'm not sensitive to it.
If I talked with them about those issues, probably they would have considerably different opinions than maybe I have.
Since at NASA you tend to work on the space shuttle and the job at hand, which has little to do with the politics of things, you don't really know how people feel about the politics of the matter.
The thing that I've noticed mostly about new astronauts is the fact that women astronauts are technically and mentally and emotionally
just as capable as male astronauts and that effect is sort of surprising because I don't think women of my generation
most of them, or many of them, had the same attitudes that would have let them be as good professional astronauts as the women of this particular generation.
And it is just an attitude.
I mean, their attitude is...
You know, it goes without saying that I'm just as capable as anybody else, regardless of sex.
And then when you watch them, they are just as capable.
Perhaps in my generation, since it would be more unusual, a woman might have an attitude that says, I'm just as capable as a man.
And to have that attitude is not as good as...
just not even hardly thinking about it, but having that feeling.
So that's the big difference I've noticed.
I've also noticed that the men and the women accept each other as the role of astronaut, just as equals, and that's just the way it is.
There's no strain or anything else that would make you think that...
The male astronauts think the female astronauts don't belong or anything like that.
How has the training changed through the presence of women?
It's not changed much at all.
The thing that occurred when we got women is we realized that many of them were smaller than the men and also that they weren't as strong in the arms and hands.
So what we did was...
was make sure that everything that had to be operated in space shuttle, like the space suits, the controls and all that, would work with the female size body and also with typical female strength.
And once we did that, then the training is pretty much the same.
If you take a job that requires this kind of strength, the man can probably do it more easily than the woman just because he's stronger.
But both of them can still do it adequately.
I relate it in my own mind to...
to trucks getting power steering.
Once trucks got power steering, women could drive trucks just as easily as men and were just as good as drivers.
Before that, it was difficult because the actual job of steering a truck was so physically demanding.
I feel that their training is no different.

you relate to a woman astronaut just like she's a male astronaut and uh nobody asks for special favors you don't see everybody treats the women nicely but i mean you they never ask to be uh excused from anything difficult or don't uh seem to feel that they have any uh special um
called to get any extra treatment or soft treatment.
And so everybody does the job, and it seems to work out real well.
The Apollo program's goal is to send man to the moon.
After this was accomplished, what was the change, or did you notice any in public opinion, Congress's attitude also towards NASA and the manned program?

Well, my feeling is that the public attitude towards anything is largely controlled by what the president wants, and then when the newspapers and television people sense what he wants, then they kind of jump on the bandwagon.
So, and Congress is sort of separate, and they...
They have their own opinion.

For example, I think that Congress related to the space program is just as much in favor of it as they ever were, and they always give you as much money as the president asked for, and they do things that the president wants done, and no problem at all.
The problem we have is getting our budget...
what we're looking for to have the president say that's what he's looking for.
So any cuts we've ever received have been from the president himself.
I think that then when the president does have an attitude, and then that is carried along to the rest of the people.
For example, if he starts talking about, if he started talking to Mara
about the fact we needed a space station.
He was very enthusiastic about it and said we told a bunch of good reasons why and there are a bunch of good reasons why we should do it and there are a bunch of good reasons why we shouldn't.

If he started talking about the good ones tomorrow and kept after it for a while and was committed to it, pretty soon the newspapers would talk about it all the time and everybody in the U.S. suddenly would be in favor of it and would talk about how wonderful and how the space program is going crazy and they like it and that's what they thought about.
If he doesn't do that, which he hasn't, then they, in my opinion, don't perceive it that way.
And everyone sort of begins to say, why is the space program different than it was?
They personally don't feel any different, but they've been barraged by the statement from the press that it's different, that they wonder why it's different.
So you seldom meet a person that doesn't feel about the space program just as he did in Apollo.
That is...
If they were in favor of it then, they're in favor of it now.
And if they weren't then, they weren't now.
So you've got to say, generally, public opinion is probably about the same from the individual.
How did that opinion affect the objectives of the pilot program?
Did that affect what you thought you could do or what you said you could do in that program?
Concern for those opinions?
Well, the opinion allowed you... Well, the opinion was that we were going to do whatever we had to do to get to the moon and back.
And we're going to give you the money to do it.
The minute you have that opinion, then you can go out and do whatever is necessary to get to the moon and back.
And you know you can.
So you have an attitude of, you know, I can do it because you know you can.
If Midway and Apollo, the president decided not to support it for one reason or another...
then it would have changed our attitude because we immediately would know we wouldn't have the money to do it.
We wouldn't have the support.
So even though technically we could do it, we wouldn't have been able to.
We'd have had to not do it.
Like now we know we could go to Mars, but nobody wants to do it.
Nobody's gonna pay to do it.
So it's not like we're running around saying, NASA's running around saying, you know, we can go to Mars.
I mean, you could, but nobody's going to pay.
So really, you'd have to say we can't.
It doesn't have the popular support.
You need popular support to get the money.
Once you get the money, you can do it.
If everybody in the country were against you and you still had the money, you could go get it done because you could hire people to do it.
probably not as efficient because people wouldn't dedicate themselves, but still in all, with the right amount of money, you could buy the technology to do it.
Okay, Congress also, in the late 60s, cut back on appropriations, which cut out the last three Apollo flights.
Looking back on that, do you feel that was a good, bad decision?
I mean, how do you feel now about that?
that cut in your budget?
Well, I feel that that's what Congress is there for.
They're there to decide where money should be spent.
And the fact they wanted to cut those out, I think from somebody in the space program, they wish they hadn't.
But at the same time, from Congress's point of view, they wish they did and did.
I mean, I don't...

I don't ever think that, personally, that one of my favorite sayings is, history draws straight with crooked lines, which fundamentally means that things eventually happen or don't happen no matter what human beings try to do about it.
So even though they vote money or don't vote money over the next 10 years, man is going to slowly get out into space.
He's going to find ways to make it profitable, and he's going to go out there more and more.
And whether it takes place 10 years from now or 20 years from now, it isn't going to make any difference.
Any more than it'd make any difference if Columbus discovered America in 1910.
I mean, who cares?
And it was important at that moment.
But sooner or later, somebody would have found out the world was round and come over here.
If it hadn't been Columbus, it would have been somebody else.
If we don't go up into space in the next 10 years, if we don't fly the last three flights to the moon, you know, who cares?
Someday people will live on the moon and they'll never worry.
It's like wondering why...
three or four white Columbus didn't take eight ships instead of three.
I mean, at the moment, at the point, he could have said as he left the country, well, look, I could start settling the New World myself if I find it.
However, we look back now, we don't know.
I mean, we can't even tell he had three ships or a hundred.
So I don't really worry about that sort of thing.
Plus, I don't think the individual, unless he's president...
can do anything about it.
And I think it's good not to worry about things you can't do anything about because it is needless worry.
You were one of 12 men to walk on the moon.
Ten years later, it's almost a, what do we have here today?
So what kind of thing?
What is there today that is a result of that?
What is the legacy?
What is the legacy?
Good question.
I think the legacy of going to the moon is just a good feeling in everybody's heart that America can do the things it wants to do.
I think that's probably the number one thing we got from it.
The other is it gives us a good feeling about what we can do in the future.
I think most of exploration has to do with just man feeling good about himself and...

wanting to do it and it lifts the human spirit and he feels good and thinks good about it and you start talking about Apollo program to anybody now they start you can see them brighten up they think about when they were where they were during Apollo and they think about where they were during the first landing and they like it it makes them feel good about America and it makes them feel good about themselves and
Even the ones that don't like the space program like that.
So I think that's what you get from something like that.
Eventually, of course, people will move out into space and live.
And so you could then say, well, if we didn't have the space program, it would have taken that much longer to go out there and begin to have settlements on the moon.
But I don't think that's really important in the long run when you do it.
You think all the money and everything else is worth it for the feeling?
Oh, yeah.
I think so.
I think probably more than that because a country's ability to survive or not depends a lot on mental attitude.
If you feel like you're a worthy country and that you can lick anything and that nobody can beat you down...
and that you can solve any problem and that you're the greatest country in the world and you're willing to sacrifice for it, that you probably can do that.

But if you get to feeling like despair and that other people are beating you and that you don't do anything right and there's really no use in trying for good goals even just because they're good, then I think that's what happens.
You know, most countries don't get...

wiped out from the outside they sort of decay from the inside and lose their spirit and everything and then somebody comes in from the outside and takes them but before that happens they've lost their spirit and I think things like Apollo keep keep your spirit up and keep you feeling competent and good and worthy and all those things like right now you just read so much about how the United States
has difficulty, can't do this.
You know, really we can, but it's just what people write about or what they talk about.
And Apollo, they think how great we were, how great this country is.
So I think it's worth that.
And I think we ought to keep doing that because we need things like that.
You need things that...
You know, the human body needs food to keep itself physically strong, and it needs exercise, and it needs something on its mind to be mentally strong and mentally feel good.
And I think Apollo made this, you know, gave us good mental vibes.
Even you talk about it now, it gives you good vibes.
You're doing a report on something that happened 10 years ago, and...
You know, it makes you feel good.
If you did one on the Vietnam War, we'd all feel bad.
So that's what you need.
You've got to have things that are good going on, and you have to pay for them.
Nothing's free, and so if you want something good going on, you're going to have to sacrifice and pay for it.
You also played a key role in Skylab.
What do you think its main returns are besides proving that man can stay in space for long periods of time?
Well, there's some scientific return.
I don't know that all that's really important.
I don't know.
I guess it's once again the good feeling you get about being part of progress and being part of great adventures and moving civilization along in a good way.
Of course, when you do all this, you build your technology and everything so that you maybe can defend yourself better if some country tried to take you over.
I don't think that's as important.
But I think a lot of it just has to do with doing something that's good.
I mean, you can spend your life trying to clean up the slums.
You ain't going to make it.
As someone said, Johnson's War on Poverty, poverty won.
It did.

He spent millions of dollars, got us in difficulties and he was going to clean up poverty and I don't know how much poverty he cleaned up, probably not all that much because it's still around and we've kind of forgotten the war on poverty.
It probably cost a hell of a lot more than going to the moon back, okay?
But...
But we remember going to the moon.
It makes us feel good.
So I think we ought to spend a lot of money to help poor people, but we're going to have to spend a lot of money to help everybody have a good feeling, too.
I mean, there's more to life than eating.
And you ought to be able to eat, and then you ought to be able to have some things for the human spirit.
And I believe things like Apollo are really great for the human spirit.
It makes us feel good.
Okay, going back to the selection process, how did it have to change for the inclusion of women?
Was there physical requirements that had to change?
Was that basically the only... Well, we knew that there weren't women that had the background.
With the shuttle, we knew we were going to need two kinds of people.
We were going to need the kind of people to fly it,
And then we're going to need the kind of people to be the scientists in it or the part scientist, part technician.
And so we realized there weren't any women pilots at the moment, although they're coming along now, that had the flying experience equal to the men.
We didn't care whether they were women and men.
We were looking for the best qualified.
So we knew we wouldn't get any women there, although we know in the future we will because women are getting in airlines and the military flying and all that other stuff.
Then the next thing was looking for the best scientist.
And we then tried to be completely arbitrary in that we tried to pick out the best scientists available without regard to the fact they were woman or man.
In other words, we...
We rated everybody according to their desirability without referencing whether they were a man or a woman.
Now that's hard to do because you know you're like some women.
coming in in addition to men.
But that was sort of the effort.
So I'm sure what we did was end up with a good combination of the best people, of which some of them fortunately turned out to be women.
As I watched the new astronauts, I felt that some of the best ones there were women.
I mean, I didn't feel like we had a bunch of great guys, you know, and then we had

number women that work too grand you know but we had to take him anyway I never felt that way and I was work close with it closely with him for a number of years I felt that some of the women were the very best there and the one characteristic I noticed about the women I felt as a group that they worked harder than the men and maybe they had to do that to make it as a woman I don't know but if you evaluated what they were doing on the weekend
or after hours or something, they usually were doing, taking flying lessons or running.
I mean, they spent more of their waking hours becoming good astronauts than the men did, I felt.
Although the men were tremendously dedicated, maybe when you find a dedicated woman, she is even more dedicated.
So that was impressive to me.
What about the other minorities?
There's blacks and Hispanic.
Do you see any difference at all, I guess, with the WASP and the minority?
I think the backgrounds of the minorities seem more different.
The background they bring...
to the astronaut corps seems more different from the older astronauts than the women bring to the astronaut corps.
So I think maybe, and all of them are not the same either, some are more closer to the same background in most of the WASP and some are further away.
I think their adjustment into the corps probably
probably is more difficult than the women.
However, the individuals we brought were very adaptable anyway, because they essentially made it in a white man's world.
Not our world, but the outside world.
So that indicates they're smart, dedicated, and they know how to adapt.
But I still think that their job of integrating
Not because of prejudice either.
I don't think you see that.
I really don't see any prejudice around there.
But just because of their background and experiences, I think they probably had a more difficult time integrating into the astronaut corps than the women did.
Can you just basically maybe go over the selection process, just the areas that you look at in the selection process?
Say education.
I've never been on a selection board, so that's one thing.
I don't know for sure.
But what it appears to do is you have a number of categories like

physical condition or physical abilities professional abilities and then finally sort of an intangible attitude abilities and so for example you give all your candidates a finalist some number that you determine are the best of the group physical examinations

uh physical tests such as hearing such as blood tests such as uh running such as all sorts of things to look at how they are physically and then when you do that then you give them sort of a grade of like one to two hundred and uh
If a person was perfect in everything, I guess he'd get 100.
But let's say if you're really good, you'd probably get 90 or 85.

Sometimes if you have some disease or some abnormality that would drop you below a certain level, then no matter how much you made in the other two areas, you couldn't make it because your physical condition wouldn't be good enough.
But you get a certain numerical rating, let's say.
And that's further broken down into areas like fiscal conditioning, where a person could improve that.
Where blood pressure, maybe they can't.

vision uh maybe they can or can't you know things like that then you look at background you just take a look and see what people have done in the past what opportunities they've had to do things for example we took people that have been out of school a long time so their experience level they ought to get a pretty good rating however we did take some people recently out of college with advanced degrees and they really had done little other than be in college and uh
and get their degree.
So they didn't have an opportunity to, let's say, make a nice discovery or write 100 papers because they hadn't been out.

So you give a grade relative to their professional competence by the fact that we have people that are competent in those fields and they can talk to them and they can go talk with their professors or the people they work with and determine how they stack up.
Then you bring them in and you have their ratings for general attitude.
You interview them.
You talk with them about what they've been doing and you can see how much of their life they've been devoting to.
trying to be this kind of a person, an astronaut kind of person, how they view it, what they would be.
And so you can get an idea of, is this the kind of person you'd like being an astronaut working with you?
Now, when they come in to be an astronaut, they have an idea of what, what it takes to do the job.
We have an idea of what it takes to do the job.
And, uh,
Somehow you've got to pick a number of people that you want to work with you on doing these exploration jobs, these astronaut things.
I don't think you end up taking the smartest people.
You don't take the physically fit people, most physically fit people.
Maybe they happen to come in.
But what you end up taking are the people that you think that you can work with to get the job done the best.

And I think sometimes that a lot of it just has to do with whether people that are there know you or know of your attitudes and know how cooperative you are and that you're a good team player and a lot of intangibles that make it difficult to pinpoint.
All these things are sort of given points and you add up the points and at the end you...
You take a look at the ones that have the highest points and you try to take them.
And you may have to do some juggling because maybe the fifth one down is the fourth geologist you've got among the top five and you don't really need that many geologists.
So maybe you take that person and don't take him and go below him and take someone else because you really need an astronomer.
And so maybe take the highest ranking astronomer who could be further down.
So there's a lot of...

give and take and a lot of it just boils down to is this the kind of person i'd like to work with and and that's true not only astronaut corps but it's true in every walk of life a lot of what you get in life has to do with how people perceive you as being cooperative or like them or you'd fit in and they can't they can't know either i mean they don't know how you're really going to fit in and uh
That's how the selection... And when women were taken, it was the same thing exactly.
I mean, they couldn't run as far maybe.
Some could run further than the guys, but same kind of thing.
And so there was really not a lot of changes for the women.
So it's mostly attitude then, just selecting.
I think it's a lot.
Yeah, I think that if you had to... As long as you... You can't be physically...
If you're physically bad, no matter what your attitude is, you've had it.
If you're professionally incompetent, no matter what your attitude is, you've had it.
But there's many more people that have those two than you can ever take.
So I think the thing you can hope to do...
is if you have those two, which many do, then it's mostly attitude, and I've found that to be true in life, period.

I mean, it's the attitude of the people that really make the difference, and it's funny, at least my experience has been looking at successful people, they all kind of have the same attitude, most of them.
You'll find an unusual one now and then that's pretty weird, but mostly they have good attitudes, and...
Even if they might not have a good attitude to people outside their field or somebody that's not working with them, to the people they work with, they have a good attitude.
Because good people wouldn't work with them if they didn't.
Because they don't want to be around people that aren't nice.
I wouldn't.
If I was around somebody I didn't like very quickly, I'd say, hey, I've got to go somewhere, and I'd just go.
I wouldn't want to be around them.
And that is the case there, too.
That's the number one thing to work on, I think.
It's hard to do, but it's profitable if you can do it.
Wouldn't you say that?
Now, this is a dog with a good attitude.
See this attitude?
Sweet doggy.
It seems to me that NASA falls into the realms of science, but until recently, scientists really weren't accepted into the program.
Why would you say that that is?
Well, I think that was because they began with no scientists.
And the group that was in control were non-scientists.
And so they were more familiar with non-scientists, pilots.
And so naturally they felt more comfortable and felt one of the rules of life is people tend to like people like themselves.
I mean, a banker may not be as crazy about other bankers, but he's comfortable with them.
And if he runs into a person that likes the same kind of thing he does and works about as hard as he does and all that, they tend to like that person and feel that person is good.
So I think that was the case.
If NASA had started out with a bunch of scientists...
then pilots would have had difficulty because scientists would have viewed pilots as flighty or hot shot.
Whereas maybe pilots viewed scientists as studious, not loose enough.
I don't know what, but I mean,
It's normal.
It's just like Americans view Frenchmen as.
Frenchmen view Americans as.
And we all know that there's just as many Frenchmen just like us as there are Americans.
So it's just the way it is, and it's gradually changing, see, because we got some early scientists in, your father, for example.
He had to kind of break the ice.
Now, you know, the scientists...
People don't think of them quite so different as they did before.
It's just part of life, you know.
I mean, if you go on a football team and everybody's 6'3", and you're 5'10", you're different.
And if you go on another team where everybody's 5'10", and you're 6'3", you're different, and you're going to have trouble fitting in.
It's just the way of human nature.
Okay, NASA's civilian organization, how has its role drifted towards the military in recent years?
Well, I don't really think NASA's role has drifted towards the military.
What has occurred is the military is going to use the shuttle.
So NASA's off here trying to get money so they can build the shuttle.
And so in order to get money from
the Air Force or the military, they've got to satisfy their requirements.
So they have to go with them and say, in order to give us money for the shuttle, what has it got to do?
And the military says, well, it's got to fly this far across range.
It's got to carry this much load and this and that.
And NASA would try to talk them out of it if it was different from their own goals.
If they couldn't, they'd then accept it.
But I don't think...
I can't tell NASA's any more...
I don't think NASA's any more military.
Don't forget the heads of NASA are not military at all, generally.
So they don't want to be military.
They don't... Once again, they...
They want...
They like civilians.
They like them.
Now, there's a few military sprinkled around, and they like them.
But if those military people don't act pretty much like civilians, they're going to remove them and put civilians in.
So...
I haven't seen NASA move to a more military way.
It may be, and I just don't notice it.
I think even if you're here a while as a military, very soon you become a civilian.
I was there 18 years, and I felt I wasn't military after two or three years.
I just didn't do military things.

I don't think, I think the astronauts would have felt that way anyway.
I think those sorts of things have more of a public opinion.
I never wanted to do anything because the Russians did.

I got to do a little bit better because Russians are trying.

How accurate do you think the intelligence that we got was in the 60s of their program?
